public disaffection with the police, a disaffection that has been growing for several years. In Canada, confidence in the police is at an all-time low. At the same time crime rates continue to rise. Canada now has the dubious distinction of having the second highest crime rate in the Western world.How did this state of affairs come about? What do we want from our police? How do we achieve policing that is consistent with the Charter of Rights and Freedoms? The essays in this volume set out to explore these questions. In their introduction, the editors point out that constitutional order is tied to the exercise of power by law enforcement agencies, and that if relations between the police and civil society continue to erode, the exercise of force will rise - a dangerous prospect for democratic societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPolice powerzCanadavCongresses. 0aPolicezCanadavCongresses. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Law Enforcement.2bisacsh1 aBraiden, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrodeur, Jean-Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedland, M.L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffiths, Curt Taylor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuth, DeLloyd J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJain, Harish C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacleod, R.C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacleod, R.C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMarquis, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobb, James C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchneiderman, David, eeditor.